Anybody using the Zimaboard for coprocessing? We’re thinking of workloads for next season that are larger than our raspberry pies can handle, and also not suitable for GPU/TPU, so we’re looking for cheap fast CPU cores, and the x86_64 is nice too.

ZimaBoard

ZimaBoard - World's First Hackable Single Board Server

ZimaBoard is world's first hackable single board server. It is a hybird of micro server and SBC (single board computer). It's designed for building a low cost NAS, media server, and software router as your home automation and entertainment center.

I’ve never used a ZimaBoard, but you can get significantly better processor at a similar/lower price and the same TDP spec if you go with an Intel N100 based mini PC on amazon. It has the added benefit of matching your team number. Beelink has been popular for PhotonVision thanks to @asid61, and they have an N100 based PC. Though it doesn’t have as neat of a case, and it does have a fan.

As another point of reference, we ran this one on our bot for 2023 without any issues (N5105 based), and they have an updated one with the N100.

Since the PC we used is powered by USB-PD, we used this regulator. It seemed to perform well enough based on some basic bench tests. We were very careful about strain relief, since the USB C connection doesn’t have features to secure it to the case.

If you pick a PC that is not USB-PD, you may need to find something else. Lots of folks ran the Beelink this past year and may have recommendations.

This is the most annoying part about using a 12V SBC, as reliable buck boost converters are rare that can support 2-3A. I would strongly recommend using an Orange Pi 5, as it is much easier to integrate and has almost as good performance as an N5095 Beelink, at a much lower price tag. The Opi5 can use any 2A 5V buck converter. 115 saw a lot of latent power drain with a beefy 19V Intel NUC this year too.

8 cores, but only 4 are “big”. Depending on what you are doing, you generally want to force your processing to only run on the 4 big cores. For my tests with PhotonVision, it produced much more stable results that way.
